s','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12223,1,12161,'Full Reference','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12224,1,12162,'Link','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12225,1,12163,'Publication was peer reviewed','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12226,1,12164,'How did Mushroom Observer help with this publication?','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12227,1,12165,'Mushroom Observer is mentioned or referenced in the publication','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12228,1,12166,'Publication List','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12229,1,12167,'List of All Publications','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12230,1,12168,'This is a list of all known publications that benefitted in some way by the existence of the Mushroom Observer. If you are aware of an article that should be added to this list please \"add it\":/publications/new. If you find an error, please add the correct citation and \"send us a note\":/email/ask_webmaster_question.','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12231,1,12169,'When possible please use the other citations as a model for how to format new ones and specifically start the citation with the family name of the lead author.','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12232,1,12170,'*P* indicates that it is a scientific, peer-reviewed article.\n*M* indicates that the article explicitly mentions or references the Mushroom Observer.','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12233,1,12171,'If you wish to cite the Mushroom Observer in a publication you are encouraged to use:\n\nWilson, N., Hollinger, J. 2006-present. Mushroom Observer. http://mushroomobserver.org\n\nHowever, your publisher may have restrictions on how or even whether websites can be sited.  If you need a published reference the best current citation we are aware of is:','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12234,1,12172,'Edit','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12235,1,12173,'Editing Publication','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12236,1,12174,'Add Publication','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12237,1,12175,'Create New Publication','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12238,1,12176,'Publication','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12239,1,12177,'Added by','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12240,2,2261,'Thank you for your interest in donating to Mushroom Observer.  To support Mushroom Observer, please send a personal gift to   Nathan Wilson either through <a href=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=2TGUG7TNXYF7Q\">PayPal</a> or you can send your checks to:\n\nNathan Wilson\n43 Cameron Rd.\nNorth Falmouth, MA 02556\n\nAs discussed in the <a href=\"/support/wrapup_2012\">2012 Wrapup</a> unlike previous years, funding for the Mushroom Observer is not being handled by the Consortium for Digital Mycology Resources (CDMR).  The CDMR is still awaiting a ruling from the IRS regarding it\'s tax exempt status.  Based on legal advice from Mushroom Observer member John Harper, a tax lawyer with Morrison & Foerster, the CDMR’s board decided not to solicit donations until the ruling is made.  However, the CDMR board of directors is committed to creating or joining a recognized tax-exempt non-profit that can receive deductible donations to support online mycological resources such as the Mushroom Observer.  Exactly what form this will take and how soon it will happen is still up in the air.\n\nIn the mean time Mushroom Observer is being supported directly by Nathan now in large part through personal gifts.  The gifts received so far will cover the current expenses over the next year.  However, the site has continued to grow and is once again needing a substantial performance boost.  The current estimate is that this will more than triple the current costs for hosting the site to roughly $200/month.\n\nThis means if you would like better performance for Mushroom Observer, please donate soon.  All such gifts will be used to cover costs directly associated with running the Mushroom Observer and will continue to be recognized on the Mushroom Observer <a href=\"/support/donors\">donors page</a>. Unfortunately, since they will be personal gifts to Nathan you will not be able to count them as tax deductible donations.\n\nBest regards and thanks for all your contributions to Mushroom Observer.','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12241,1,12178,'2012 Wrapup for the Mushroom Observer Community','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12242,1,12179,'2012 was a busy year for Mushroom Observer.  Many notable new features were added.  Highlights include:\n\n* Substantial revisions to the <a href=\"/name/show_name/383\">Show Name</a> and <a href=\"/image/show_image/267480?size=medium\">Show Image</a> pages\n* Data downloads from observation searches\n* Support for <a href=\"/herbarium\">Herbarium</a> and Specimen pages\n* Interactive support for translators\n* <a href=\"/observer/checklist?user_id=1093\">Life Lists</a> from user summary pages\n* Substantial increase in data shared with EOL\n* Reciprocal links with <a href=\"http://mycoportal.org/\">MyCoPortal</a>\n\nMore details available on the <a href=\"/observer/news\">Features and Fixes</a> page.\n\nOne of the goals of this work has been to increase the scientific value of the site for research. The support for Herbarium and Specimen pages as well as the reciprocal links with MyCoPortal are recent steps towards this goal. This work is directly related to a new effort to digitize fungal herbaria throughout the US led by Barbara Thiers. I continue to work with Tom Bruns at UC Berkeley and Deborah McGuinness at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute (RPI) to find funding to directly support improvements to the Mushroom Observer.  These projects continue to promise exciting developments for MO in the future.\n\nIn addition, the site has continued to grow.  We now have over 300,000 images, 100,000 observations, and over 3800 registered users.  This not only indicates the greatest number of images we\'ve received in a year (106,000), but is a greater growth rate than the previous year (56% vs. 49%).\n\nFortunately, due to generous donations from all of you, we have continued to be able to improve the site configuration.  While we do have a few more tricks up our sleeves that we expect to implement soon, it is increasingly clear that more substantial improvements are needed.  Historically, we have run the site off a single server.  To achieve the next level of performance we would like to separate the database from the application server, and add an additional application server along with a small load balancer.  We expect this to roughly triple the monthly costs of running the site to around $200/month.\n\nI am also excited by a recent surge in the number of folks interested in contributing their time to the Mushroom Observer development effort.  We had a summer intern, Han Wang, from RPI create a prototype system for describing Fungi using semantic web technology (references at the end of the letter).  I presented on this work at the 2012 Mycological Society of America annual meeting.  Another RPI student, Katie Chastain, has recently joined the team and is interested in working on data provenance and developing a workflow for species discovery.  Alan Rockefeller has begun looking into improving site performance and Joe Cohen has started exploring upgrading our software stack.  If you want to join the party, sign up for the new <a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups=#!forum/mo-developers\">mo-developers@googlegroups.com</a> mailing list.  One of the significant enabling pieces for this is a new simpler system for setting up a development environment.  You can find out more at the <a href=\"https://github.com/MushroomObserver/developer-startup\">developer-startup GitHub Project</a>.\n\nHowever, this year has not been entirely good news. The Consortium for Digital Mycology Resources (CDMR), was organized in 2009 to support online digital mycology resources such as Mushroom Observer, and it applied for federal tax exempt status under section 501(&zwj;c&zwj;)3 so that it could receive deductible donations from interested users.  This ruling is still pending in the IRS.  Beginning in 2012, Mushroom Observer member John Harper, a tax lawyer with Morrison & Foerster, noticed that CDMR’s exemption application had been pending with the IRS for an unusually long time, and volunteered to help CDMR on a pro-bono basis in its attempt to attempt to obtain recognition of a section 501(&zwj;c&zwj;)3 status for CDMR.  Since then he has briefed the IRS on the issues that the IRS has raised, and had a conference with the IRS to discuss the ruling request.  CDMR’s case is currently under review in the National Office of the IRS.\n\nIn light of CDMR’s unsettled tax status, CDMR’s board decided not to solicit donations at the end of last year.  However, the CDMR board of directors is committed to creating or joining a recognized tax-exempt non-profit that can receive deductible donations to support online mycological resources such as the Mushroom Observer.  Exactly what form this will take and how soon it will happen is still up in the air.\n\nWithout financial support from CDMR, I have been personally paying to support Mushroom Observer largely out of my own pocket over the last few months. I would very much appreciate any <a href=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=2TGUG7TNXYF7Q\">personal gifts</a> that you all would be willing to send to contribute to the cost of keeping Mushroom Observer online during this interim period. This will be especially important before we can attempt to improve the level of performance by adding more servers. Any gifts I receive will be used to cover costs directly associated with running the Mushroom Observer and such donations will continue to be recognized on the Mushroom Observer donors page. Unfortunately, you will not be able to count them as tax deductible donations.  You can make your gifts with a credit card through <a href=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=2TGUG7TNXYF7Q\">PayPal</a> or you can send your checks to:\n\nNathan Wilson\n43 Cameron Rd.\nNorth Falmouth, MA 02556\n\n\nThanks for all your contributions to the Mushroom Observer,\n-Nathan','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12243,2,2295,'Advanced search was added in February, 2009 to [:app_title].  There are a lot of directions this feature could go.  I have intentionally kept it somewhat limited since I am concerned that it may have performance issues that result in timeouts.  Please send \"email to the webmaster\":/email/ask_webmaster_question if you experience timeouts or if there are particular types of searches you would like to have added.\n\nHints : It\'s okay to leave some of the fields blank, e.g., if you leave \'Observer\' blank, it will return results by all [:users]. It matches the exact string given.  Use \"OR\" (all caps) to tell it to match one of several possible strings, e.g. \"Xanthoria OR Xanthomendoza\".  Use a star as a wildcard, e.g. \"Wells Gray*Canada\" will match \"Wells Gray, Canada\", \"Wells Gray Park, Canada\", and \"Wells Gray Provincial Park, Canada\".  (See notes under \'Content\', too.)','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12244,2,2382,'*Create List:* Click a genus in the first column to pull up a list of species in that genus.  Select any of these taxa and press return or double-click to add species to your list.  Accepted names are in boldface; deprecated names are followed by one or more accepted alternatives.  You may choose any.  To remove a name, select it in the third column, and press delete or double-click.  (You may also use arrows to navigate, or type partial names to search within a column.)\n\n*Save List:* When you are finished, click any of the buttons at the bottom of the page.  \"Create [:species_list]\" takes you back to the old creation form, where you will be able to enter date, location, notes, etc. before saving the list.\n\n*Reports :* The plain text report gives you a simple list of taxa with no formatting.  Rich text can be used to import the list into Microsoft Word complete with authors and all the formatting intact.  Spreadsheet produces a CSV file, with name, author, citation, and accepted columns.  Common names are not available yet.  Reports should automatically download in a separate tab or window; if not, go to your browser\'s File menu and click \'Save As\'.','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12245,1,12180,'documentation','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12246,1,12181,'github','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12247,1,12182,'glossary','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12248,1,12183,'herbarium','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12249,1,12184,'images','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12250,1,12185,'observations','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12251,1,12186,'pivotal','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12252,1,12187,'publications','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12253,1,12188,'upgrade','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12254,1,12189,'vagrant','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12255,1,12190,'Date created','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12256,1,12191,'Date last modified','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12257,1,12192,'Date of last activity','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12258,1,12193,'[:refine_search_time_help]','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12259,1,12194,'[:refine_search_time_help]','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12260,1,12195,'The RedCloth manual.','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12261,1,12196,'The old hobix.com tutorial.','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12262,1,12197,'Cheatsheet courtesy warpedivisions.org.','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12263,2,2705,'__italics__        trademark(tm)  \\\n**boldface**       copyright(c)    | (must follow letters, not punctuation)\n+underline+        registered(r)  /\n@monospace@\n^superscript^      1.6 &amp;&#109;icro;m  ->  1.6 &micro;m\n~subscript~        34&amp;&#100;eg;17\' N  ->  34&deg;17\' N\n\n\"External Link\":http://google.com or !http://random.com/image.jpg!\n\nInternal links:\n_name 371_, _Amanita ocreata_, or _A. ocreata_\n_location 382_, _location Mt. Wilson_\n_user 252_, _user jason_\n_observation 12345_\n_image 12345_, !image 12345!, or !image 640/12345!\n_comment 12345_\n\nInclude footnote[[1]] references after any word[[2]].\n\nfn1. And then define the footnote at the bottom.\n\nfn2. Be sure to leave blank lines around these \"xx.\" directives.\n\nh1. Header\n\nbq. Block quote or indent a paragraph.\n\n* bullet list item 1\n* bullet list item 2\n\n# numbered list item 1\n# numbered list item 2\n\nTables are useful for comparing species:\n| Species 1 | value 1.1 | value 1.2 |\n| Species 2 | value 2.1 | value 2.2 |\n| Species 3 | value 3.1 | value 3.2 |','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12264,3,2762,'Please help us make this website available around the world!  It\'s easy.\n\nThere are approximately 3000 lines with 25000 words of text on this site at the moment, but don\'t let that scare you.  We\'ve organized it so someone with limited time can concentrate on the most important text.  Then as time and energy permits, they or someone else can continue working down the list until one day it is all finished.\n\nThere are several ways to get started.  You can pick up a copy of the entire \"translation file\":[repo] and start translating it into any language you wish.  \"Send us an email\":/email/ask_webmaster_question to learn more about this approach.\n\nIt\'s even easier to work on existing translations.  Just look for \"[:app_edit_translations]\" at the bottom of any page.  You can see immediately how your changes look in the context of the page.  If your language is not available, \"send us an email\":/email/ask_webmaster_question and we can create a \"beta\" version for you to work on.\n\nYou will, of course, receive credit and contribution bonus for each line you translate, in addition to the gratitude of countless users.','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12265,1,12198,'Created translation for [tag].','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12266,1,12199,'Created on','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12267,2,2798,'Hi [login],\n\nWe\'ve noticed that email to your address is bouncing.\n\nPlease check the address we\'re using and make sure it is correct.\n\nEmail : [email]\n\n\"Click here to change it.\":/account/prefs\n\n[notes]','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12268,1,12200,'Created','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12269,1,12201,'Created','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12270,2,2968,'User wants to merge two locations, both with observations:\n\nuser : [user]\nthis : [this]\ninto : [that]\nloc1 : [this_url]\nloc2 : [that_url]','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12271,2,11497,'User made nontrivial change to a name:\n\nuser : [user]\nold : [old]\nnew : [new]\nobservations : [observations]\nnamings : [namings]\nname : [url]','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12272,2,2969,'User wants to merge two names, both with observations:\n\nuser : [user]\nthis : [this]\ninto : [that]\nname1 : [this_url]\nname2 : [that_url]','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12273,2,2991,'*Purpose&#58;* The purpose of this site is to record observations about mushrooms, help people identify mushrooms they aren\'t familiar with, and expand the community around the scientific exploration of mushrooms (mycology).  Some have asked what counts as a mushroom.  This site takes a very broad view.  While the emphasis is on the large fleshy fungi, other fungi such as lichens, rust and molds as well as fungus-like organisms such as slime-molds are all welcome.  Ultimately, I hope this site will become a valuable resource for both amateur and professional mycologists.  I like to think of it as a living field guide for mushrooms or a collaborative mushroom field journal.\n\nFor those new to mycology, there is a huge amount of basic research that still needs to be done.  By some estimates less than 5% of the world\'s species of fungi are known to science.  While things are slightly better for the large fleshy fungi known as mushrooms, it is still a common experience to come across a mushroom that cannot be easily identified in the available books or which doesn\'t really fit the definition of any recognized species. This site is intended to address that gap by creating a place for us to talk about and record what we\'ve found, as well as connect to the existing literature about mushrooms.  Please do not feel intimidated by the scientific bent of the site.  Everyone is welcome to dive in and add their own mushroom observations, upload mushroom photos and make [:comments] on other people\'s observations.','2014-09-05 13:04:39',0),(12274,2,2992,'*Image Sharing:* This site follows the principles of cooperative sharing pioneered by the \"Free Software Foundation\":http://fsf.org, further expressed by the \"Open Source software movement\":http://opensource.org, and expanded to other creative efforts by the \"Creative Commons\":http://creativecommons.org. Consequently all images are made available under one of the Creative Commons licenses or are in the public domain.  In short this means that when anyone uploads one of their images to the site, they are giving others explicit permission to use those images under certain \"conditions\":/info/how_to_use#license in perpetuity.  This type of permission is very important for basic research.  It allows future researchers to freely use these data to expand our understanding of mushrooms.  It also significantly increases the likelihood that the data will continue to be available into the distant future.\n\nIf you upload your own images, this license does not mean you are giving up your copyright or your ability to make money off your images.  Depending on which license you choose, you can still require that anyone who wishes to use any of these images for commercial purposes get in touch with the copyright holder and work out the conditions for that use.  The site includes special links on the image pages to help create those relationships.','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12275,1,12202,'h2. 2. Scientists\n\np(normal).  Mention Mushroom Observer in your publications and \"add references to your publications\":/publications.','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12276,2,3008,'*Keeping Up with Changes* - The default page for [:app_title] is the \'[:rss_log_title]\', it is also accessible through the \'\"Latest Changes\":/\' link in the left-hand panel.  This page shows you the most recent changes on the site.  It lists new \"Observations\":#observation and \"Species Lists\":#species_list as well as significant changes to any already existing ones.  Additions of \"Images\":#image and \"Comments\":#comment are considered significant changes to the relevant observations.  Changes to \"Names\":#name are also listed.  Click the page numbers at the top and bottom of the page to browse through older changes.  Observations and names created as a side effect of other changes are not listed separately.\n\nNote : The latest changes can be tracked using our \"RSS feed\":/observer/rss. See this \"wikipedia article\":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rss for more information about RSS feeds.','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12277,2,3011,'*Adding Observations You Have Identified* - Use the same process as \"Getting Help with an Unknown\":#unknown_help, except this time provide your identification in the \'[:WHAT]\' field.  You are strongly encouraged to say something about how you arrived at the identification.  We\'ve provided a small set of checkboxes to make this easy (\'[:naming_reason_label_1]\', \'[:naming_reason_label_3]\', etc.), but you are encouraged to elaborate on them in the provided text fields (e.g., list the references you used, or enter \'sequenced the DNA and compared it against the data in GenBank\'!). Community members will often post \"Comments\":#comment if there is some question about the collection or if they would like clarification as to why you ruled out other \"Names\":#name.  Roy Halling has provided beautifully illustrated presentations describing <a href=\"http://mushroomobserver.org/pdf/macro-features.pdf\">macroscopic</a> and <a href=\"http://mushroomobserver.org/pdf/micro-features.pdf\">microscopic</a> features. More documentation on creating scientifically valuable collections is available from the <a href=\"http://mycoportal.org/portal/misc/links.php\">MycoPortal Links Page</a>.','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12278,2,3016,'*Describing Species* - Click any \"Name\":#name link you see throughout the site.  For example, click any of the results listed in \"[:app_index_a_z]\":/name/observation_index, search for a name in the search bar, or click the \'About &lt;&#110;ame&gt;...\' link at the top of any \"Observation\":#observation page.  These all take you to a page summarizing everything we know about this taxon.  If you are familiar with this species and there is something you would like to add, click \'[:show_name_edit_name]\' and add your notes.  You are encouraged to cite references including field guides and scientific papers.  Short quotes from references are fine, but please don\'t make extensive quotes without obtaining permission from the original author.','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12279,2,3018,'*Working with Maps* - Currently there are three types of maps available on [:app_title]: Occurrence Maps (e.g., \"Occurrence map for **__Craterellus cornucopioides__**\":/name/map/284), Location Maps (e.g., \"Salt Point State Park\":/location/show_location/4) and the \"[:map_locations_global_map]\":/location/map_locations.\n\nTo see an occurrence map for a particular \"Name\":#name, go to the page for that name (e.g., enter the name in the search bar, select \'[:NAMES]\'), and click \'[:app_search]\', then click \'[:show_name_distribution_map]\' at the top of the page.\n\nUsers are encouraged to add to the occurrence map for a name.  The easiest way is to create a new \"Observation\":#observation using an already defined \"Location\":#location.  Note, however, that auto-completion for the \'[:WHERE]\' field will list all matching locations whether they are defined or not.\n\nYou can also explicitly choose not to have an observation show up on the occurrence map.  This allows you to record observations of mushrooms in places like mushroom fairs, old photos or other places where you may not know where the mushroom was actually collected.  When creating or editing an observation there is a checkbox labeled \'[:form_observations_is_collection_location]\'.  By default it is checked.  If you uncheck it, that observation will not appear in any occurrence maps.','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12280,2,3019,'*Defining Undefined Locations* - Many \"Observations\":#observation have been reported from undefined \"Locations\":#location.  These observations will not appear in our \"occurrence maps\":#maps.  An excellent, easy way for \"Users\":#user to help out if they have a little spare time is to locate and define these undefined locations.\n\nWhen browsing through observations, defined location names will be followed by a link labeled \'[:click_for_map]\'.  Undefined location names will be followed by a link labeled \'[:SEARCH]\'.  If you click the link for an undefined location, it will show a list of observations reported for that location.  The resulting page will include two links at the top of the page: \'[:list_observations_location_define]\' and \'[:list_observations_location_merge]\'.  Clicking on \'[:list_observations_location_define]\' will present a form which you can use to create that location.  Clicking on \'Merge With a Defined Location\' will present you with a list of similar locations which have already been defined.  Clicking on any of these locations will perform the merge.\n\nYou can also see a list of all locations in use by clicking on \'\"[:app_list_locations]\":/location/list_locations\' in the left-hand panel. This page lists both the defined locations (first column, sorted alphabetically) and the undefined locations (second column, sorted by the number of observations reported from that location).  In some cases the same location has been given multiple names (e.g., \'Point Reyes National Seashore\' and \'Pt Reyes Park\').  You can merge an undefined location with a defined location by clicking on \'[:list_place_names_merge]\' next to the undefined location (see above).\n\nWhen defining a new location, the first thing to do is to review its name. Mushroom Observer tries to enforce a set of \"rules\":/location/help.\n\nIn theory it is possible for the same location to be defined more than once (presumably by different users).  If this happens, you can request a merge by editing one of the two locations and changing its name to be exactly the same as the other\'s.  This will not have any immediate effect, but it will display a warning message, and an email will be sent to the site administrators with the details.  Merging defined locations is restricted since it can cause significant data loss.','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12281,2,3025,'*Image* - A photograph or illustration of one or more mushroom species. Images are associated with one or more \"Observations\":#observation.  A given Image is owned by a particular \"User\":#user who may or may not be the copyright holder.  Only the owner or a site administrator can remove an image or edit the associated information.  All images in the site are required to be released under one of the \"Creative Commons licenses\":http://creativecommons.org or in the public domain.  If you dispute the given copyright or the licensing of an image you are the copyright holder of, send mail to the \"webmaster\":/email/ask_webmaster_question.','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12282,2,3026,'*License* - \"Images\":#image on [:app_title] are posted with an explicit license.  The current options are the \"Creative Commons Attribution, Share Alike License\":http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/, the \"Creative Commons Attribution, Non-Commercial, Share Alike License\":http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/ and \"Public Domain\":http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Public_domain/.  The primary difference is whether the image can be used in any potentially commercial setting.  One of the side effects of selecting the non-commercial license is that your image cannot be used on \"Wikipedia\":http://wikipedia.org.  The license can be set on a per image basis.  The looser, Wikipedia compatible license is the default for new \"Users\":#user.  However, you can select the non-commercial license to be your default by selecting it on your \'\"[:app_preferences]\":/account/prefs\' page and clicking on \'[:SAVE_CHANGES]\'.  Public domain is supported primarily for images that are already in the public domain or for images from certain government institutions that cannot claim ownership of works','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12283,2,3111,'[:validate_missing(field=:user_group)]','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12284,1,12203,'[:validate_missing(field=:publication_full)]','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12285,1,12204,'Successfully created [type].','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12286,1,12205,'No [types] matching \'[value]\' found.','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12287,1,12206,'Successfully updated [type].','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12288,1,12207,'[:runtime_created_at(type=:naming)]','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12289,1,12208,'[:runtime_updated_at(type=:naming)]','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12290,2,11880,'Bad key \"[key]\".','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12291,1,12209,'Unexpected file attached.','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12292,1,12210,'[TYPES] Matching \'[regexp]\'','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12293,1,12211,'Date Created','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12294,1,12212,'Time Last Modified','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12295,2,1508,'[:sort_by_updated_at]','2014-09-05 13:04:40',0),(12296,1,12213,'one','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12297,1,12214,'ignore','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12298,1,12215,'Ignore','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12299,1,12216,'Herbaria','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12300,2,12085,'Glossary Term','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12301,2,12086,'glossary term','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12302,2,12087,'Glossary Terms','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12303,2,12088,'glossary terms','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12304,2,925,'Elevation','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12305,2,926,'elevation','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12306,1,12217,'Select file...','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12307,1,12218,'No file selected.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12308,1,12219,'','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12309,1,12220,'[:log_object_updated_by_user(type=:project)]','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12310,1,12221,'[:log_object_updated_by_user(type=:species_list)]','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12311,2,12113,'[:log_object_created_by_user(type=:glossary_term)]','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12312,2,12114,'[:log_object_updated_by_user(type=:glossary_term)]','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12313,3,11947,'Enjoy our new user interface!  Many thanks to <a href=\"http://mushroomobserver.org/users/show_user/6261\">Ray Suelzer</a> and <a href=\"http://mushroomobserver.org/users/show_user/4468\">Joe Cohen</a> for most of the work.<br>See the <a href=\"http://mushroomobserver.org/observer/news\">Release Notes</a> for details.  Of course, <a href=\"http://mushroomobserver.org/email/ask_webmaster_question\">send us a note</a> if you see anything wrong.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12314,2,1614,'Release','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12315,1,12222,'Your Lists','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12316,1,12223,'More','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12317,1,12224,'Other','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12318,1,12225,'Sorry, someone else has given this a positive vote, so we had to create a new Naming to accomodate your changes.\"','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12319,2,1697,'Edit Name [name]','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12320,1,12226,'Camera Date','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12321,1,12227,'Uploading Images','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12322,1,12228,'Creating Observation','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12323,3,1789,'Optional GPS location. Latitude is expected to be between -90.0 and 90.0 and longitude between -180.0 and 180.0. Elevation will be converted to meters. If you choose to provide this data please make it as accurate as possible. Examples: \"34.1164\" = \"34°6&apos;59&quot;N\", \"-118.1459\" = \"118 8.754 W\", \"239 m\" = \"784 ft.\"','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12324,1,12229,'Use the checkboxes on the left to select the image you would like to use as the thumbnail for this observation. In the file select dialog you can select multiple images at a time.  You can also continue to add additional images by clicking the button below.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12325,1,12230,'Use this date','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12326,1,12231,'Note: The camera date on some of your photos doesn\'t match the observation date you have entered.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12327,1,12232,'Set observation date to','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12328,1,12233,'Set image dates to','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12329,1,12234,'This image is too large. Images must be less than [:max]Mb in file size.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12330,2,1840,'Send Commercial Inquiry','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12331,1,12235,'Countries with Observations','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12332,2,1912,'Latest Release: July 3, 2015','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12333,2,1913,'This page provides notes on the latest release of the [:app_title] website.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12334,1,12236,'Hi All,\n\nIf you are reading this, then we have finally gotten out a new release for Mushroom Observer that we\'ve been working on for months.\n\nThe original goal of this release was to update our infrastructure to something more recent (Rails 4.0 for those who care about such things).  This upgrade was spearheaded by Joe Cohen.  However, some of these infrastructure changes required major changes to the way we handle our user interface (UI).  Fortunately, Ray Suelzer stepped forward and undertook the daunting task of bringing the Mushroom Observer UI into the current decade.  This is a huge change that has literally affected every interface in the system.  Along the way some significant UI changes were made which we think overall will improve the experience of using the site for everyone.\n\nThat being said, the underlying data model, voting and naming system, etc. has not changed.  We hope to go after some of these known issues soon, but our first goal has had to be bringing the underlying systems up to date.  While this particular upgrade is significant, it is, unfortunately, not the end of the road for needed infrastructure upgrades. However, we hope that this new release has laid the groundwork for making those additional updates much easier.\n\nThat being said, here\'s a list of the biggest changes that have happened to the Mushroom Observer interface:\n\n<b>New Layout</b> - The most obvious change that you will see is that there is a new layout. The primary goals of the new layout were to make the website friendly for mobile devices, and to create a cleaner and simpler user experience. We tried to keep the feel of the site largely the same, but we did make some significant changes along the way. Here are the changes in the layout, why we made them, and how they might impact you.\n\n<ol><li><p><b>Removed \"matrix\" style boxes</b>. This is the most significant change to the layout. The old layout used HTML tables to render content into different squares. While this worked very well when the site was initially coded, the rise of mobile phones and smaller devices required us to abandon having a fixed number of columns per row. When viewing the site on a smaller screen the content will automatically switch to a smaller number of columns so you can view content just as easily on a phone as on a computer. This change required us to drop the existing preference of defining how many columns and rows you would like to show on each page, since we want to automatically display the information in a format that reasonably fits your screen. Instead, you can now set how many results you would like to display on each page. The framework we are working with supports three screen resolutions and we have tuned the site to work with the most standard screen sizes given our content.  As a result we could not find an easy way to support the small number of users who have chosen to use an increased number of columns presumably for very large screens.  If this has a big effect on your workflow, please let us know and we\'ll see if we can work out something that addresses your needs.</p></li><li><p><b>Left Navigation Bar Changes</b> -<ol><li>We looked at the analytics of which links people were using most frequently and reordered the navigation bar to reflect this usage. This should ultimately provide for an easier experience for everyone, but there may be a bit of transition pain for those who have become used to the old layout. We also added a link to \"Your Lists.\"</li><li>We reduced the number of items in the sidebar by putting the different language options in a dropdown, which will make it easier for users to find the more frequently used links more quickly.</li><li>On mobile devices the Navigation Bar will now slide out from the side with a \"hamburger\" button. This gives users the experience they expect when viewing a website on their phone.</li><li>Most of the items related to your account have moved to the top navigation bar.</li></ol></p></li><li><p><b>Top Navigation Bar</b> - The search bar remains at the top, but we have added some special icons for the user to the far right.<ol><li>If you are not logged in, you will see two buttons \"Create an Account\" or \"Login\".</li><li>If you are logged in you will see a few new icons.<ol><li>The \"cog\" or \"gear\" will take you to the user preference page.</li><li>The \"inbox\" will take you to see comments for you.</li><li>The \"horn\" will take you to see all of the different observations or other items that you are following.</li><li>The \"door\" will sign you out.</li><li>If you click on your username, you will see a dropdown of more actions associated with your account. Such as showing your observations, species lists, and your summary.</li></ol></li></ol></p></li></ol>\n\n<b>Images</b> - We spent time thinking about how we deal with images on the website. We decided that some of the current options should be replaced with a more modern experience. Here is a list of changes that relate to images.<ol><li><p><b>Theater View</b> - When you hover over any image on the site with your mouse, you will see an \"expand\" icon appear in the top right of the image. Clicking this will open the image in full-screen. You can close the view by pressing escape, clicking the \"X\" button in the top right, or clicking in the grey area outside of the image. If you want to view or download the original image, simply click on the image in the full-screen.</p></li><li><p><b>Show Image Page</b> - The show image page previously allowed a user to set the default image size to anything from \"small\" to \"huge\". The reality of this feature was that setting the default size to anything larger than \"medium\" caused the image to go off of the screen and degraded the experience of the page. To that end, the show image page will default to showing the image to be as large as will fit on your screen. If you want to see the image even larger, you can click the \"theater\" button and if you want to see the original image size, which with today’s cameras will not fit on even the largest of screens, you can click the image after it appears in full-screen view. In most modern browsers this will allow you to zoom in to full resolution.</p></li><li><p><b>Images on show observation page</b> - Discussed more in the changes to the \"show observation\" page below.</p></li></ol>\n\n<b>Changes to Show Observation Pages</b> - The most commonly viewed page on MO is the show observation page. As such, we took some time reworking how this page is laid out and attempted to simplify the design to make an observation more easily digestible at first glance.<ol><li><p><b>Images front and center</b> - The most useful information in an observation is often the images. As such we added an image carousel that will display the images at the top of the page and allow a user to scroll back and forth through the images. We also wanted to reduce the clutter on the page, but still allow users to access important information about images such as notes and (where available) the original filename. These data are now hidden, but you can see them by simply placing your mouse over one of the images.</p></li><li><p><b>Moved information about the \"name\" of the observation to its own box</b> - Previously this information was found up top in the title, we felt that this information was too useful to hide up there so it was placed in its own box above the \"map\".</p></li><li><p><b>Map</b> - The map now resizes to fit the screen it is being viewed on.</p></li><li><p><b>Species Lists</b> - Species lists associated with the observation are now on the right.</p></li><li><p><b>Proposed Names</b> - Proposed names and namings were given more space to breathe and are displayed directly under the images.</p></li><li><p><b>Comments</b> - The layout for how comments look was updated to be a cleaner and are now shown directly at the bottom.<p></li></ol>\n\n<b>Dismissible Top Banner Messages</b> - We wanted to retain a way to notify users of important updates and changes across the top of the page in a message banner, but to allow users to hide the banner after they have read the message. By clicking the \"x\" button on the top banner, it will be hidden for a month, or until something else important comes up.\n\n<b>Tweaks to create observation page</b> - We wanted users to be able to quickly add observations from their phones and clean up the create observations page. The updated create observation page is mobile friendly and a user can upload images directly from their phone and create an observation.\n\n<b>And much more...</b> - Many other more subtle changes and tweaks were made to the site that we hope improve the overall experience on Mushroom Observer.  We think everyone will get something out of the new changes and we have tested things pretty throughly, but we will not be surprised if we missed somethings.  Please let us know if you see something strange or broken or if there are further user interface changes that you would like to see.\n\nWe hope you enjoy the new interface!\n\nThe Mushroom Observer Development Team','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12335,2,2048,'Highest Elevation','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12336,2,2049,'Lowest Elevation','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12337,1,12237,'On MyCoPortal','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12338,2,2160,'Joined','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12339,2,12151,'Create New Glossary Term','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12340,2,12152,'Add Glossary Term','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12341,2,12157,'[:edit_object(type=:glossary_term)]','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12342,2,12158,'Editing Glossary Term: [name]','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12343,2,12160,'Only admins can edit glossary terms','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12344,2,12015,'Original Herbarium Label','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12345,1,12238,'(initial determination and unique herbarium id)','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12346,3,2261,'Thank you for your interest in donating to Mushroom Observer.  To support Mushroom Observer, please send a personal gift to   Nathan Wilson either through <a href=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=2TGUG7TNXYF7Q\">PayPal</a> or you can send your checks to:\n\nNathan Wilson\n68 Bay Rd.\nNorth Falmouth, MA 02556\n\nAs discussed in the <a href=\"/support/wrapup_2012\">2012 Wrapup</a> funding for the Mushroom Observer is no longer being handled by the Consortium for Digital Mycology Resources (CDMR).  The CDMR is now in the process of dissolving and the expectation is that a new non-profit focused solely on Mushroom Observer will be created.\n\nIn the mean time Mushroom Observer is being supported directly by Nathan now in large part through personal gifts.  All such gifts will be used to cover costs directly associated with running the Mushroom Observer and will continue to be recognized on the Mushroom Observer <a href=\"/support/donors\">donors page</a>. Unfortunately, since they will be personal gifts to Nathan you will not be able to count them as tax deductible donations.\n\nBest regards and thanks for all your contributions to Mushroom Observer.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12347,2,2266,'Thank you for offering to make the following gift.  To complete this transaction using PayPal, click the button below.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12348,2,12179,'2012 was a busy year for Mushroom Observer.  Many notable new features were added.  Highlights include:\n\n* Substantial revisions to the <a href=\"/name/show_name/383\">Show Name</a> and <a href=\"/image/show_image/267480?size=medium\">Show Image</a> pages\n* Data downloads from observation searches\n* Support for <a href=\"/herbarium\">Herbarium</a> and Specimen pages\n* Interactive support for translators\n* <a href=\"/observer/checklist?user_id=1093\">Life Lists</a> from user summary pages\n* Substantial increase in data shared with EOL\n* Reciprocal links with <a href=\"http://mycoportal.org/\">MyCoPortal</a>\n\nMore details available on the <a href=\"/observer/news\">Features and Fixes</a> page.\n\nOne of the goals of this work has been to increase the scientific value of the site for research. The support for Herbarium and Specimen pages as well as the reciprocal links with MyCoPortal are recent steps towards this goal. This work is directly related to a new effort to digitize fungal herbaria throughout the US led by Barbara Thiers. I continue to work with Tom Bruns at UC Berkeley and Deborah McGuinness at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute (RPI) to find funding to directly support improvements to the Mushroom Observer.  These projects continue to promise exciting developments for MO in the future.\n\nIn addition, the site has continued to grow.  We now have over 300,000 images, 100,000 observations, and over 3800 registered users.  This not only indicates the greatest number of images we\'ve received in a year (106,000), but is a greater growth rate than the previous year (56% vs. 49%).\n\nFortunately, due to generous donations from all of you, we have continued to be able to improve the site configuration.  While we do have a few more tricks up our sleeves that we expect to implement soon, it is increasingly clear that more substantial improvements are needed.  Historically, we have run the site off a single server.  To achieve the next level of performance we would like to separate the database from the application server, and add an additional application server along with a small load balancer.  We expect this to roughly triple the monthly costs of running the site to around $200/month.\n\nI am also excited by a recent surge in the number of folks interested in contributing their time to the Mushroom Observer development effort.  We had a summer intern, Han Wang, from RPI create a prototype system for describing Fungi using semantic web technology (references at the end of the letter).  I presented on this work at the 2012 Mycological Society of America annual meeting.  Another RPI student, Katie Chastain, has recently joined the team and is interested in working on data provenance and developing a workflow for species discovery.  Alan Rockefeller has begun looking into improving site performance and Joe Cohen has started exploring upgrading our software stack.  If you want to join the party, sign up for the new <a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups=#!forum/mo-developers\">mo-developers@googlegroups.com</a> mailing list.  One of the significant enabling pieces for this is a new simpler system for setting up a development environment.  You can find out more at the <a href=\"https://github.com/MushroomObserver/developer-startup\">developer-startup GitHub Project</a>.\n\nHowever, this year has not been entirely good news. The Consortium for Digital Mycology Resources (CDMR), was organized in 2009 to support online digital mycology resources such as Mushroom Observer, and it applied for federal tax exempt status under section 501(&zwj;c&zwj;)3 so that it could receive deductible donations from interested users.  This ruling is still pending in the IRS.  Beginning in 2012, Mushroom Observer member John Harper, a tax lawyer with Morrison & Foerster, noticed that CDMR’s exemption application had been pending with the IRS for an unusually long time, and volunteered to help CDMR on a pro-bono basis in its attempt to attempt to obtain recognition of a section 501(&zwj;c&zwj;)3 status for CDMR.  Since then he has briefed the IRS on the issues that the IRS has raised, and had a conference with the IRS to discuss the ruling request.  CDMR’s case is currently under review in the National Office of the IRS.\n\nIn light of CDMR’s unsettled tax status, CDMR’s board decided not to solicit donations at the end of last year.  However, the CDMR board of directors is committed to creating or joining a recognized tax-exempt non-profit that can receive deductible donations to support online mycological resources such as the Mushroom Observer.  Exactly what form this will take and how soon it will happen is still up in the air.\n\nWithout financial support from CDMR, I have been personally paying to support Mushroom Observer largely out of my own pocket over the last few months. I would very much appreciate any <a href=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=2TGUG7TNXYF7Q\">personal gifts</a> that you all would be willing to send to contribute to the cost of keeping Mushroom Observer online during this interim period. This will be especially important before we can attempt to improve the level of performance by adding more servers. Any gifts I receive will be used to cover costs directly associated with running the Mushroom Observer and such donations will continue to be recognized on the Mushroom Observer donors page. Unfortunately, you will not be able to count them as tax deductible donations.  You can make your gifts with a credit card through <a href=\"https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=2TGUG7TNXYF7Q\">PayPal</a> or you can send your checks to:\n\nNathan Wilson\n68 Bay Rd.\nNorth Falmouth, MA 02556\n\n\nThanks for all your contributions to the Mushroom Observer,\n-Nathan','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12349,1,12239,'descriptions','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12350,1,12240,'javascript','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12351,1,12241,'mobile','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12352,1,12242,'prefs','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12353,1,12243,'rss','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12354,1,12244,'specimens','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12355,1,12245,'tests','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12356,1,12246,'textile','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12357,1,12247,'users','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12358,2,2727,'Hold your mouse over any of the fields in the table below to see what the field is supposed to be.  The text fields are, in order: notes (top right), date, location, latitude, longitude, elevation (second row).  Check boxes indicate, respectively, if location is where collected, and specimen.  All links open in new tabs.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12359,2,2914,'Naming Notification - [name]','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12360,2,2998,'h4. 1. Contributors\n\np(normal).  Beyond adding pictures and descriptions of mushrooms that you\'ve seen, you can make a big difference to the site by \"describing species\":/info/how_to_use#describing_species or \"defining locations\":/info/how_to_use#defining_locations.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12361,2,12202,'h4. 2. Scientists\n\np(normal).  Mention Mushroom Observer in your publications and \"add references to your publications\":/publications.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12362,2,3000,'h4. 3. Developers\n\np(normal).  We have \"lots of ideas\":[todo_list] about how to improve the site.  The framework, Ruby on Rails, is really easy to pick up and we are more than happy to mentor anyone who wants to dive in.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12363,2,3001,'h4. 4. Translators\n\np(normal). The site is set up to support foreign languages.  All we need is someone to do the translations.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12364,2,3002,'h4. 5. Donors\n\np(normal). Help support our server costs by \"donating\":/support/donate to the Mushroom Observer.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12365,2,3003,'h4. 6. Business Planning\n\np(normal).  So far [:app_title] has been an entirely volunteer effort, after some time consuming false starts, we are now in the process of creating a new non-profit focused solely on Mushroom Observer. This is just getting going so let us know if you want to get involved or have any business related advice.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12366,2,3153,'Elevation must be real number in feet or meters.  Feet will be converted to meters (default).  Examples:\n1234\n1234m\n4049\'\n4049 ft.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12367,2,11892,'Invalid elevation, \"[val]\", examples: \"1234\", \"1234m\", \"4048\'\", \"4048ft\".','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12368,1,12248,'Invalid or unknown herbarium, \"[val]\", accept numerical id, code or name.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12369,1,12249,'The parameter, \"[field]\", can only be used if the observation has a specimen.','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12370,1,12250,'Please only use one of these parameters: [fields].','2015-08-03 02:10:55',0),(12371,4,11947,'1. The old MO Listserver email list is defunct. If you want to be on a general email list, please join the <a href=\"http://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/mo-general\">MO General Forum</a>. <br/>2. Names and Observations now have links to MycoBank.<br/>3. Enjoy our new user interface!<br>See <a href=\"/observer/news\">Release Notes</a> for details. Of course, <a href=\"/email/ask_webmaster_question\">send us a note</a> if you see anything wrong.','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12372,2,1799,'Check any species lists you would like to add this observation to.','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12373,1,12251,'Set as default thumbnail','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12374,2,1823,'Default thumbnail','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12375,3,1912,'Latest Release: August 3, 2015','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12376,2,12236,'August 3, 2015. <u>MycoBank Links</u>\n\nNames and Observations now include links to a MycoBank search for the named taxon. If Mycobank has an official translation in your MO Language, the search will take you to that translation.\nWhy not also Index Fungorum? Unfortunately Index Fungorum does not currently provide for this kind of search.\n\n\nJuly 3, 2015. <u>New UI, Rails 4.0 upgrade</u>\n\nHi All,\n\nIf you are reading this, then we have finally gotten out a new release for Mushroom Observer that we\'ve been working on for months.\n\nThe original goal of this release was to update our infrastructure to something more recent (Rails 4.0 for those who care about such things).  This upgrade was spearheaded by Joe Cohen.  However, some of these infrastructure changes required major changes to the way we handle our user interface (UI).  Fortunately, Ray Suelzer stepped forward and undertook the daunting task of bringing the Mushroom Observer UI into the current decade.  This is a huge change that has literally affected every interface in the system.  Along the way some significant UI changes were made which we think overall will improve the experience of using the site for everyone.\n\nThat being said, the underlying data model, voting and naming system, etc. has not changed.  We hope to go after some of these known issues soon, but our first goal has had to be bringing the underlying systems up to date.  While this particular upgrade is significant, it is, unfortunately, not the end of the road for needed infrastructure upgrades. However, we hope that this new release has laid the groundwork for making those additional updates much easier.\n\nThat being said, here\'s a list of the biggest changes that have happened to the Mushroom Observer interface:\n\n<b>New Layout</b> - The most obvious change that you will see is that there is a new layout. The primary goals of the new layout were to make the website friendly for mobile devices, and to create a cleaner and simpler user experience. We tried to keep the feel of the site largely the same, but we did make some significant changes along the way. Here are the changes in the layout, why we made them, and how they might impact you.\n\n<ol><li><p><b>Removed \"matrix\" style boxes</b>. This is the most significant change to the layout. The old layout used HTML tables to render content into different squares. While this worked very well when the site was initially coded, the rise of mobile phones and smaller devices required us to abandon having a fixed number of columns per row. When viewing the site on a smaller screen the content will automatically switch to a smaller number of columns so you can view content just as easily on a phone as on a computer. This change required us to drop the existing preference of defining how many columns and rows you would like to show on each page, since we want to automatically display the information in a format that reasonably fits your screen. Instead, you can now set how many results you would like to display on each page. The framework we are working with supports three screen resolutions and we have tuned the site to work with the most standard screen sizes given our content.  As a result we could not find an easy way to support the small number of users who have chosen to use an increased number of columns presumably for very large screens.  If this has a big effect on your workflow, please let us know and we\'ll see if we can work out something that addresses your needs.</p></li><li><p><b>Left Navigation Bar Changes</b> -<ol><li>We looked at the analytics of which links people were using most frequently and reordered the navigation bar to reflect this usage. This should ultimately provide for an easier experience for everyone, but there may be a bit of transition pain for those who have become used to the old layout. We also added a link to \"Your Lists.\"</li><li>We reduced the number of items in the sidebar by putting the different language options in a dropdown, which will make it easier for users to find the more frequently used links more quickly.</li><li>On mobile devices the Navigation Bar will now slide out from the side with a \"hamburger\" button. This gives users the experience they expect when viewing a website on their phone.</li><li>Most of the items related to your account have moved to the top navigation bar.</li></ol></p></li><li><p><b>Top Navigation Bar</b> - The search bar remains at the top, but we have added some special icons for the user to the far right.<ol><li>If you are not logged in, you will see two buttons \"Create an Account\" or \"Login\".</li><li>If you are logged in you will see a few new icons.<ol><li>The \"cog\" or \"gear\" will take you to the user preference page.</li><li>The \"inbox\" will take you to see comments for you.</li><li>The \"horn\" will take you to see all of the different observations or other items that you are following.</li><li>The \"door\" will sign you out.</li><li>If you click on your username, you will see a dropdown of more actions associated with your account. Such as showing your observations, species lists, and your summary.</li></ol></li></ol></p></li></ol>\n\n<b>Images</b> - We spent time thinking about how we deal with images on the website. We decided that some of the current options should be replaced with a more modern experience. Here is a list of changes that relate to images.<ol><li><p><b>Theater View</b> - When you hover over any image on the site with your mouse, you will see an \"expand\" icon appear in the top right of the image. Clicking this will open the image in full-screen. You can close the view by pressing escape, clicking the \"X\" button in the top right, or clicking in the grey area outside of the image. If you want to view or download the original image, simply click on the image in the full-screen.</p></li><li><p><b>Show Image Page</b> - The show image page previously allowed a user to set the default image size to anything from \"small\" to \"huge\". The reality of this feature was that setting the default size to anything larger than \"medium\" caused the image to go off of the screen and degraded the experience of the page. To that end, the show image page will default to showing the image to be as large as will fit on your screen. If you want to see the image even larger, you can click the \"theater\" button and if you want to see the original image size, which with today’s cameras will not fit on even the largest of screens, you can click the image after it appears in full-screen view. In most modern browsers this will allow you to zoom in to full resolution.</p></li><li><p><b>Images on show observation page</b> - Discussed more in the changes to the \"show observation\" page below.</p></li></ol>\n\n<b>Changes to Show Observation Pages</b> - The most commonly viewed page on MO is the show observation page. As such, we took some time reworking how this page is laid out and attempted to simplify the design to make an observation more easily digestible at first glance.<ol><li><p><b>Images front and center</b> - The most useful information in an observation is often the images. As such we added an image carousel that will display the images at the top of the page and allow a user to scroll back and forth through the images. We also wanted to reduce the clutter on the page, but still allow users to access important information about images such as notes and (where available) the original filename. These data are now hidden, but you can see them by simply placing your mouse over one of the images.</p></li><li><p><b>Moved information about the \"name\" of the observation to its own box</b> - Previously this information was found up top in the title, we felt that this information was too useful to hide up there so it was placed in its own box above the \"map\".</p></li><li><p><b>Map</b> - The map now resizes to fit the screen it is being viewed on.</p></li><li><p><b>Species Lists</b> - Species lists associated with the observation are now on the right.</p></li><li><p><b>Proposed Names</b> - Proposed names and namings were given more space to breathe and are displayed directly under the images.</p></li><li><p><b>Comments</b> - The layout for how comments look was updated to be a cleaner and are now shown directly at the bottom.<p></li></ol>\n\n<b>Dismissible Top Banner Messages</b> - We wanted to retain a way to notify users of important updates and changes across the top of the page in a message banner, but to allow users to hide the banner after they have read the message. By clicking the \"x\" button on the top banner, it will be hidden for a month, or until something else important comes up.\n\n<b>Tweaks to create observation page</b> - We wanted users to be able to quickly add observations from their phones and clean up the create observations page. The updated create observation page is mobile friendly and a user can upload images directly from their phone and create an observation.\n\n<b>And much more...</b> - Many other more subtle changes and tweaks were made to the site that we hope improve the overall experience on Mushroom Observer.  We think everyone will get something out of the new changes and we have tested things pretty throughly, but we will not be surprised if we missed somethings.  Please let us know if you see something strange or broken or if there are further user interface changes that you would like to see.\n\nWe hope you enjoy the new interface!\n\nThe Mushroom Observer Development Team','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12377,2,1921,'Appearance Settings','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12378,2,11473,'View thumbnail map on Observation page?','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12379,1,12252,'List page items','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12380,1,12253,'View Observer identification of Observations?','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12381,2,1946,'Privacy Settings','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12382,2,12237,'on MyCoPortal','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12383,1,12254,'on MycoBank','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12384,1,12255,'Site ID','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12385,1,12256,'Observer ID','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0),(12386,1,12257,'When checked, causes Observations to display Observer ID (the observer\'s choice of name for the taxon), if it is different from consensus and if observer is sufficiently confident of his/her identification.','2015-11-07 22:55:42',0);
